Sep 26 2009 	A British Hotel Gem	My husband and I chose this hotel after reading that it was one of the few, independently owned British hotels left in London. We did not want a large, overdone chain hotel because we wanted to experience English charm. Durrants Hotel delivered. Even our friends, who are British, commented on what a lovely place it was.We did not find the place worn and tattered as other reviewers mentioned, but beautifully decorated with lovely art work, furniture and old wood paneling. The room, although a bit small, was nicely decorated, air-conditioned, with a large flat screen TV on the wall opposite the bed (we didn't watch it however). It faced the back which was very quiet. We would have liked to have had a coffee pot in the room but the dining staff was happy to bring one up in the mornings. The bed afforded us the most comfortable sleep with nice linens, soft down pillows, and perfect weight blanket (MY husband and I do not like sleeping under duvets as we get way too hot). And there was good lighting on either side of the bed for reading - something we did not always have in other places.The location was perfect, on a very quiet street in the West End, yet minutes from Marylebone, Oxford St. shopping, restaurants and the Bond and Baker Street underground. It was great coming back to the hotel and getting away from the crowds after a long day. The staff was always pleasant upon arrival and departure, friendly and courteous. The hotel also has a car service you can use (about the same price as a cab to Paddington, then 2 tickets for the Heathrow Express) for door to door service to Heathrow Airport. This really avoids hassles when leaving and takes only about 35 minutes.Our 3 nights at Durrants were extremely pleasant and we were very happy with our choice.	
