Jul 18 2009	Truly English hotel	I love this hotel. It's built in an 18th century house with a double stair case. It has a magnificent bar with wood pannelling and a comfortable breakfast room/restaurant with white table clothes and beautiful heavy silver plated cutlery and proper toast racks. Breakfast is wonderful and is served directly at your table (no buffet). You can have stewed prunes, porridge, a really astringent yoghurt and muesli, fresh juices and of course the full English. The rooms (I've stayed there twice) are extremely cosy and old fashioned with comfortable beds and soft pillows. The linen includes cotton face clothes which are changed daily which is a nice touch. They also have a lounge area with comfortable tub chairs where you can get a beautiful afternoon tea presented in a proper pot with scones and clotted cream. They do the most wonderful old fashioned sandwiches. You can get beef sandwiches made with real roast beef and chicken as opposed to the awful plastic variety you tend to get elsewhere. If you were tired in the evening, they have a restaurant serving meals from 6pm onwards. I've never eaten there but the menu looks good and there were some lovely smells emanating from the dining room. On the occasions I stayed there it was full of the most wonderful English people you only read about in books. I once heard the most amazing conversation between an English World War Two veteran in a wheel chair with the most beautiful plummy accent and a young German girl tending the reception. It was surreal to hear the two of them talk about the war with him saying 'Oh well it is forgiven and forgotten now' and her saying 'oh no, not forgotten'.On the last occasion I was there standards had slipped slightly; the pleasant German girl was no longer on reception and it was manned with a rather unpleasant girl and our room had to be changed because the heating no longer worked but all in all these were relatively small issues and as a treat this is a hotel I would recommend to a friend. Note also that it is very near to Oxford and Bond Street and Marleybone High Street which is full of great restaurants little boutiques.	
