Jan 6 2008 	Happy Stay at Durrants	I spent four happy nights at Durrants in mid-November.I liked the location, warm and comfortable interiors, and friendly and helpful staff -- and I was happy to get the quiet room I requested. As someone who likes to read and sometimes work in bed, I particularly liked the plentiful lighting in my room -- in addition to the lamps on the two bedside tables, there were large lamps on the desk and a chest of drawers, as well as a charming old hanging fixture in brushed gold. (I don't do well in some trendy hotels where the guestrooms are as dimly lit as the hotel bar downstairs.) The bath and closet area had modern recessed lighting.My room had nice antique/old furniture, quality fabrics, linens and wallpaper, charming old prints, and was in excellent condition and perfectly maintained by the housekeeping staff. There was also nightly turndown service. I was surprised to see reviews here by people who stayed at the hotel at about the same time I did and described it as &quot;worn out&quot; and &quot;in need of a face lift.&quot; But I suppose it's a matter of taste, and to some the words &quot;antique&quot; and &quot;old&quot; may be synonymous with &quot;worn out&quot; and &quot;in need of a face lift.&quot;I especially recommend this hotel to people who like traditional, characterful, independently owned British/European hotels. After the recent demise of both Topham's and the Basil Street Hotel, it was heartening to find this hotel still in business and in good form.I don't think I would recommend this hotel to people who like big modern American-style hotels. Nor would I recommend it to those for whom the latest in American business amenities is important -- for them I might recommend nearby hotels like the Churchill, in Portman Square, which has recently become a Hyatt Regency, or the SAS Radisson, across the street from the Churchill. However, Durrants does seem popular with UK/European business people during the week.I recommend booking Durrants through the Durrants website -- which offers both last-minute deals and package deals. I paid the rack rate one night and got a weekend package the other three nights. The average nightly rate was about US $350, which included both VAT and English breakfast. (I live in New York City and can't imagine getting comparable accommodation here during the busy autumn season for that price.) Everything I saw on Expedia and similar sites was more expensive. The Durrants website also has details on the different types of guestrooms.	
